dfa6f899-373d-4f20-bf4d-3a3939c5aac1.0ea6e41b-0618-4cab-9d3e-3a470a763612.description=

This step checks whether documentIncomplete is matches with Y or not.

Inputs\:
    matchType -Exact Match
    toMatch - documentIncpomlete
    matchTo - Y
    ignoreCase - True

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success -documentIncomplete matches with Y
    failure - documentIncomplete Not matches with Y

dfa6f899-373d-4f20-bf4d-3a3939c5aac1.3929e355-750c-45c7-913d-af2280499e6e.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database using the information in the tnsnames.ora file.  

Inputs\:
    TNSPath- The path to the folder of the TNS file tnsnames.ora. This path must be accessible by the OO RAS service. For example, if the RAS and the Oracle server are installed on the same Windows system, the TNSPath might look like “C\:\app\Administrator\product\11.1.0\db_1\network\admin”. If the RAS and the Oracle server are on different Windows systems, you can copy the tnsnames.ora file to the RAS system, then the TNSPath might look like “C\:\Program Files\Hewlett-Packard\Operations Orchestration\RAS\Java\Default\webapp\conf” or “C\:\Temp” depending on where you place the .ora file. 
    TNSEntry - The entry name in the tnsnames.ora file that contains the connection information. The value for this input is case insensitive. For example, the value for the TNSEntry input is “TestEntry”  if the content in the tnsnames.ora file looks like the following\: 

TestEntry \=
  (DESCRIPTION \=
   (ADDRESS \= (PROTOCOL \= TCP)(HOST \= 16.110.111.111)(PORT \= 1521))
   (CONNECT_DATA \=
     (SERVER \= DEDICATED)
     (SERVICE_NAME \= orcl)
   )
 )

    Username - The username to connect to the Oracle database. 
    Password - The password for the Username.
    Command - The command to execute. 
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution.
Default values\: 0 

Results\:
    returnResult - Specifies whether the command executed successfully. 
    outputText - The output of the command execution. 
    updateCount - The update count of the command executed.

Responses\:
    success - The command executed successfully.
    failure - Failed to execute the command.

Notes\:
1. This operation only supports Oracle.
2. It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below show the syntax to use for a PL/SQL script\:

BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}
dfa6f899-373d-4f20-bf4d-3a3939c5aac1.458c0522-7acf-4ea7-9bd5-9cb83813453a.description=
This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
dfa6f899-373d-4f20-bf4d-3a3939c5aac1.5f80e89f-314a-4f9e-b9c8-3dc719deabe8.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

dfa6f899-373d-4f20-bf4d-3a3939c5aac1.b7164eb1-ebe7-4245-9d87-0e9d5f263bba.description=Retrieves a system account username and password and stores the values as flow variables. Inputs\: accountName - The name of the system account. Starting with OO Platform version 10.20, the relative path of the system account can also be used. flowVariable - The flow variables prefix to store the system account into. The operation will receive one input with the flow variable name to assign to, but will actually assign the account to two separate variables. So if the input flowVar was "sysAcct" then two flow vars will be created "sysAcctUsername" and "sysAcctPassword". Results\: Result - A message indicating if the operation was successful or not.
